1
00:00:03,080 --> 00:00:05,280
Hey, when are we getting there, Dad?

2
00:00:05,360 --> 00:00:08,240
In a week.
-What’s that? Why are you snapping at the kid?

3
00:00:08,320 --> 00:00:09,520
She started it.
-Started what?

4
00:00:09,600 --> 00:00:11,040
She just asked when we’re getting there.

5
00:00:11,120 --> 00:00:12,240
Yeah, but why did she say "Hey, really"?

6
00:00:12,320 --> 00:00:14,880
Because she got her mom's genes too.
-Oh, so talk to her nicely.

7
00:00:14,960 --> 00:00:17,000
She might also have your dad's genes
for getting offended.

8
00:00:17,080 --> 00:00:20,360
Okay, you’re right, honey, we really created a new breed.
-Yeah.

9
00:00:20,840 --> 00:00:23,080
Are you guys joking with me?
-No, honey, of course not, God forbid.

10
00:00:23,160 --> 00:00:24,440
No, honey, what did you want to know, sweetie?

11
00:00:24,520 --> 00:00:26,440
Where are we going?
-We’re going...

12
00:00:27,920 --> 00:00:29,280
Wait, where are we really today?

13
00:00:30,880 --> 00:00:32,560
What, where did we eat last Friday?

14
00:00:32,640 --> 00:00:33,960
I suddenly don’t remember.

15
00:00:35,120 --> 00:00:37,640
Everything’s turned into one big mix
of Shabbat hugs and kisses.

16
00:00:38,360 --> 00:00:39,800
Shabbat Shalom.
-Shabbat Shalom.

17
00:00:39,880 --> 00:00:40,960
Shabbat Shalom.

18
00:00:41,040 --> 00:00:42,880
Shabbat Shalom.
-Shabbat Shalom.

19
00:00:42,960 --> 00:00:44,240
Shabbat Shalom.

20
00:00:44,920 --> 00:00:46,880
Shabbat Shalom.
-Shabbat Shalom.

21
00:00:46,960 --> 00:00:49,240
Shabbat Shalom.
-Shabbat Shalom.

22
00:00:49,320 --> 00:00:51,480
Shabbat Shalom.

23
00:00:58,200 --> 00:01:00,800
Look at me, look at me and...

24
00:01:08,960 --> 00:01:10,000
Where are we going?

25
00:01:10,080 --> 00:01:12,640
If you had the option to choose,
where would you want to go?

26
00:01:12,720 --> 00:01:14,320
Tell me, what are you doing?
-Just a question.

27
00:01:14,400 --> 00:01:15,440
What question? It’s like asking the kid

28
00:01:15,520 --> 00:01:16,960
who do you love more, Mom or Dad.

29
00:01:17,040 --> 00:01:19,120
What are you talking about?
-There’s no choice here, honey,

30
00:01:19,200 --> 00:01:23,240
my parents work really hard
on Friday night so you can eat on Shabbat.

31
00:01:23,400 --> 00:01:24,360
I’m not the only one eating.
-Okay,

32
00:01:24,440 --> 00:01:26,600
but you probably don’t understand how hard it is
to host everyone.

33
00:01:26,680 --> 00:01:28,320
I understand very well, you’d be surprised,

34
00:01:28,400 --> 00:01:30,080
but even in my family, it’s a hassle.

35
00:01:30,160 --> 00:01:32,040
I’m really surprised.
-Sit down...

36
00:01:32,120 --> 00:01:33,560
Honey, maybe you don’t know,

37
00:01:33,640 --> 00:01:36,960
but for us, the preparations for Friday
start already on Tuesday.

38
00:01:45,840 --> 00:01:47,560
Is everything okay?
-Yeah, why?

39
00:01:48,040 --> 00:01:49,440
I don’t know, you look a bit stressed.

40
00:01:49,520 --> 00:01:51,920
I was just thinking about what I need to cook for Friday,

41
00:01:52,480 --> 00:01:53,560
what I need to buy.

42
00:01:54,400 --> 00:01:57,200
Suddenly I find myself
once again with all the same things

43
00:01:57,280 --> 00:02:00,360
again and again and again,
enough, I’m tired of it, I don’t want to.

44
00:02:00,440 --> 00:02:02,080
It really is tiring.
-What’s tiring?

45
00:02:02,160 --> 00:02:04,480
What, you don’t like it?
-I like it, what, no...

46
00:02:04,560 --> 00:02:07,360
Did I say I don’t like it? What’s not good?
I like it, I like it a lot.

47
00:02:07,720 --> 00:02:09,479
You just said you’re tired of it, and so am I...

48
00:02:11,760 --> 00:02:14,240
I mean, if you’re tired of it...

49
00:02:14,400 --> 00:02:16,200
Hey, do you understand?
-Of course I understand.

50
00:02:16,280 --> 00:02:17,280
Okay, then.

51
00:02:17,400 --> 00:02:19,920
No, I’m not making anything, that’s it.
-Great, for once,

52
00:02:20,480 --> 00:02:23,600
for once don’t make anything, thank you, that’s all.

53
00:02:24,600 --> 00:02:27,480
I’ll make a bowl of macaroni and that’s it.

54
00:02:27,600 --> 00:02:31,800
Don’t bother, please, let’s just order from a restaurant for once.

55
00:02:31,880 --> 00:02:34,080
What restaurant? Why do we need a restaurant?

56
00:02:34,160 --> 00:02:38,160
What, all that macaroni takes 20 minutes,
including boiling the water and the sauce.

57
00:02:38,520 --> 00:02:40,040
What’s that, macaroni isn’t food? It’s not good?

58
00:02:40,600 --> 00:02:42,600
Okay, it’s food, it’s good, it’s food,

59
00:02:42,680 --> 00:02:45,120
I’m backing you up on this, okay?

60
00:02:45,200 --> 00:02:46,320
And that’s it.

61
00:02:46,400 --> 00:02:48,400
Really, that's it.
-And that's it.

62
00:02:48,480 --> 00:02:53,400
Tell me, is the macaroni sauce
with meat or without?

63
00:02:53,480 --> 00:02:55,520
What, I already made Bolognese, come on.

64
00:02:55,600 --> 00:02:58,560
So on Thursday, we need to defrost the ground meat.

65
00:02:59,760 --> 00:03:01,120
And that's it, that's it.

66
00:03:01,720 --> 00:03:03,320
Wait, Sali, wait, wait,

67
00:03:03,400 --> 00:03:05,720
If I'm already defrosting
the ground meat on Thursday,

68
00:03:05,800 --> 00:03:08,120
then I can use some of it
to make Manny's meatballs,

69
00:03:08,200 --> 00:03:09,040
so you won't cry.

70
00:03:09,120 --> 00:03:11,920
What’s the deal? It’s the same prep time, that’s it.
-Fine.

71
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:13,160
You know what?

72
00:03:13,240 --> 00:03:16,120
The girls don’t even have to mix
the meatballs with the rice.

73
00:03:16,200 --> 00:03:18,480
What are you talking about? Rice is unrelated.

74
00:03:18,720 --> 00:03:21,520
I have to make rice
because that’s the only thing they eat.

75
00:03:21,600 --> 00:03:22,640
I always make rice.

76
00:03:22,720 --> 00:03:27,840
And Moshe can whine until tomorrow morning
that he doesn’t have a pakala, tough luck.

77
00:03:28,040 --> 00:03:30,720
Orna.
-What now, Orna?

78
00:03:30,800 --> 00:03:34,320
No, she’ll start with the "Why does Manny get meatballs |

79
00:03:34,400 --> 00:03:35,560
and Moshe doesn’t get a pakala?"

80
00:03:35,640 --> 00:03:38,960
I don’t have the energy for this headache,
I’ll make the pakala.

81
00:03:39,240 --> 00:03:41,920
Fine, that’s it.
-That’s it, we need to buy beans.

82
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:42,840
Okay.

83
00:03:44,240 --> 00:03:46,720
There’s one more thing, but it’s not about food,
it’s a medical issue.

84
00:03:46,800 --> 00:03:50,280
Alin, she’s anemic, and the doctors recommend
that an anemic woman eat iron,

85
00:03:50,840 --> 00:03:53,600
so a little peas will do the trick.

86
00:03:54,080 --> 00:03:57,440
You can tell you’re a guy, you don’t understand anything.
-Fine.

87
00:03:58,280 --> 00:03:59,520
He has a lot of work.

88
00:03:59,600 --> 00:04:01,920
What about the eggplants?
-Eggplants, of course, eggplants.

89
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:03,880
I really, really love your eggplants.

90
00:04:03,960 --> 00:04:05,400
Eggplants, that’s it.
-That’s it.

91
00:04:05,480 --> 00:04:07,480
And again, I’m doing the same things.
-Right.

92
00:04:09,440 --> 00:04:11,800
And you think it’s easier at my parents’?
-Of course.

93
00:04:11,920 --> 00:04:12,920
You’re so wrong.

94
00:04:13,480 --> 00:04:15,520
It might not start on Tuesday
because of the number of guests,

95
00:04:15,680 --> 00:04:16,760
but the hysteria is no less.

96
00:04:19,640 --> 00:04:21,120
Pinchas.
-Huh?

97
00:04:21,200 --> 00:04:24,000
How many people are coming over for dinner?

98
00:04:24,840 --> 00:04:27,880
As usual.
-What kind of answer is "as usual"?

99
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:31,600
Do you want me to answer you "as usual"
when you ask me where your underwear is?

100
00:04:31,680 --> 00:04:33,520
Sorry, Riki, I just woke up.

101
00:04:33,640 --> 00:04:36,200
Well, we know more or less who’s coming, right?

102
00:04:36,280 --> 00:04:39,200
More or less is the least accurate there is.

103
00:04:39,280 --> 00:04:43,040
I don’t want to just throw away food,
I’m making my dish with the apples

104
00:04:43,200 --> 00:04:46,440
and I want to put in exactly, not less, not more.

105
00:04:48,880 --> 00:04:51,520
Why the silence?
-I’m counting in my head.

106
00:04:52,120 --> 00:04:54,520
Not sure I want you counting in your head

107
00:04:55,240 --> 00:04:57,520
when I send you to the store to buy seven things

108
00:04:57,640 --> 00:05:00,880
and you forget one,
save your head for the pillow.

109
00:05:01,080 --> 00:05:03,400
Okay, what do you want me to do?

110
00:05:03,920 --> 00:05:05,360
I want you to call Adam

111
00:05:05,920 --> 00:05:08,480
and ask him if he’s coming alone
or with his date.

112
00:05:08,560 --> 00:05:10,920
I don’t want to bother him over something silly.

113
00:05:11,120 --> 00:05:14,240
Just add one more apple
!If she comes, then she’ll have it.

114
00:05:14,320 --> 00:05:17,040
And if she doesn’t come? What, am I going to throw away food?

115
00:05:17,320 --> 00:05:19,560
Isn’t that a shame, Pinchas? It costs money,

116
00:05:20,360 --> 00:05:24,120
I don’t remember the last time we got
a call from Gabriela from the lottery.

117
00:05:24,280 --> 00:05:26,400
Ariella.
-What, do you know her?

118
00:05:26,480 --> 00:05:27,320
No.

119
00:05:27,520 --> 00:05:28,400
Then call her.

120
00:05:28,480 --> 00:05:31,200
That way he’ll see we’re thinking of him.

121
00:05:31,280 --> 00:05:34,240
You know what, if she doesn't eat
then I'll eat, okay?

122
00:05:34,320 --> 00:05:36,240
Why, are you a garbage can?

123
00:05:36,800 --> 00:05:40,400
Don't you have enough calories and cholesterol
in the pantry?

124
00:05:40,600 --> 00:05:42,080
Go call him.
-Okay.

125
00:05:45,120 --> 00:05:46,480
Hello, hello.

126
00:05:46,680 --> 00:05:49,000
Dad, can you talk to him later?

127
00:05:49,560 --> 00:05:51,800
Oh, you're the...

128
00:05:52,360 --> 00:05:53,360
Yeah.

129
00:05:53,440 --> 00:05:54,760
Son.
-What’s up?

130
00:05:54,840 --> 00:05:55,680
He's busy.

131
00:05:55,760 --> 00:05:57,960
Did he answer you?
-Yeah, but he's busy.

132
00:05:58,520 --> 00:05:59,800
What do you mean he's busy?

133
00:06:00,480 --> 00:06:02,640
It's a simple question, yes or no,

134
00:06:02,720 --> 00:06:04,400
No need for a seminar for that.

135
00:06:04,480 --> 00:06:07,360
I know, Riki, I'll call him
in 15 minutes, okay?

136
00:06:07,960 --> 00:06:11,200
And what am I supposed to do? Wait a quarter of an hour?

137
00:06:11,400 --> 00:06:13,760
Why don't I have a life of my own? I'm bored?

138
00:06:14,320 --> 00:06:16,520
Riki, he's busy, he's in the middle of something, come on.

139
00:06:17,280 --> 00:06:19,160
Call him now while he’s still answering,

140
00:06:19,240 --> 00:06:21,600
in a quarter of an hour he’ll be swamped.

141
00:06:22,160 --> 00:06:24,400
Okay, okay, just don’t get mad.
For real.

142
00:06:26,640 --> 00:06:29,800
What, Dad, is it urgent?
-Adam, just answer me yes or no.

143
00:06:29,880 --> 00:06:32,560
Yes, Dad, I'm still busy, bye.
-Come on, Adam...

144
00:06:34,480 --> 00:06:37,200
He didn't answer me, he's probably really busy,

145
00:06:37,280 --> 00:06:38,800
let's respect his privacy.

146
00:06:39,600 --> 00:06:42,680
Why doesn't he respect my time?

147
00:06:43,200 --> 00:06:47,680
I think when we call him
he should answer us right away.

148
00:06:48,160 --> 00:06:51,880
What if the kid suddenly has an accident
or some unexpected death?

149
00:06:51,960 --> 00:06:55,320
In our family, there’s no unexpected death,
it’s expected all the time.

150
00:06:55,400 --> 00:06:57,640
Death doesn’t bother us as long as we’re alive.

151
00:06:58,920 --> 00:07:02,800
Fine, fine, belittle me,
yell at me, kill me,

152
00:07:02,880 --> 00:07:07,600
I don’t understand what big deal you made
out of a simple little question,

153
00:07:07,880 --> 00:07:09,640
is he coming alone or not.

154
00:07:10,240 --> 00:07:11,120
What’s the big deal?

155
00:07:11,200 --> 00:07:12,880
Fine, let me handle it myself.

156
00:07:13,880 --> 00:07:16,480
I don’t understand why I have to
do everything alone in this house.

157
00:07:16,560 --> 00:07:19,400
Riki.
-You wouldn’t last a minute without me.

158
00:07:19,840 --> 00:07:22,760
I just hope I die first
so you can see you were right.

159
00:07:23,320 --> 00:07:25,440
Fine, talk, talk to him, see he’s busy.

160
00:07:26,240 --> 00:07:29,680
Hello.
-Adam, I don’t care if you’re busy or not,

161
00:07:30,240 --> 00:07:31,760
I want you to answer me right away,

162
00:07:31,840 --> 00:07:34,800
are you coming alone or with your latest diva?

163
00:07:35,280 --> 00:07:38,840
So yeah, I’ll come with her, okay?
-Alright, mama's boy.

164
00:07:39,560 --> 00:07:42,480
You know Mom loves you the most
in the world, right, Adam?

165
00:07:42,600 --> 00:07:44,880
Yeah.
Alright, Mom, bye.
-Bye, sweetheart.

166
00:07:46,120 --> 00:07:47,920
Come on, was that so hard?

167
00:07:48,640 --> 00:07:50,360
When I talked to him, it was hard.

168
00:07:52,720 --> 00:07:54,840
Sorry, my mom.

169
00:07:56,080 --> 00:07:57,800
I think he’s worried about his mom.

170
00:07:57,880 --> 00:07:59,600
That’s why he brings someone different every week.

171
00:08:00,360 --> 00:08:02,640
Alright, let’s skip the prep stage
and focus on the shopping stage.

172
00:08:03,120 --> 00:08:04,160
Of course, poor his dad.

173
00:08:04,640 --> 00:08:05,920
Poor him? My dad’s the one who’s poor.

174
00:08:06,480 --> 00:08:09,080
Because shopping for us usually
never ends.

175
00:08:13,200 --> 00:08:16,680
Sali, I forgot some things,
I need you to go to the store.

176
00:08:17,440 --> 00:08:20,520
Oh, not fun.
-It’s nothing, I made you a little list,

177
00:08:20,800 --> 00:08:22,520
I need you to go quickly and come back fast.

178
00:08:22,600 --> 00:08:27,320
How can I go and come back fast,
just the line at the checkout is over an hour.

179
00:08:27,400 --> 00:08:29,000
No, no, you don’t have to wait an hour,

180
00:08:29,080 --> 00:08:31,160
you can go to the express checkout for ten items.

181
00:08:32,280 --> 00:08:33,720
Nine, ten, eleven.

182
00:08:33,840 --> 00:08:35,840
What eleven?
-There are eleven items.

183
00:08:35,919 --> 00:08:37,120
Come on, it’s nothing, so eleven.

184
00:08:37,200 --> 00:08:38,840
What do you mean nothing? Why is it nothing?

185
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:43,120
I’ll stand there, and some know-it-all will come
and say: with all due respect, sir,

186
00:08:43,200 --> 00:08:44,520
there are more than ten items,

187
00:08:44,600 --> 00:08:46,720
just stand there, in the regular checkout.

188
00:08:46,800 --> 00:08:48,040
I have to stand there later.

189
00:08:48,120 --> 00:08:49,880
Spare me that, son, just take it.

190
00:08:49,960 --> 00:08:52,160
Silvan.
-Rachel.

191
00:08:52,640 --> 00:08:54,720
Alright, son, take one off, give up something.

192
00:08:54,800 --> 00:08:55,920
Please, then take it off.

193
00:08:56,000 --> 00:08:58,240
You can take off the black coffee, quietly.

194
00:08:58,320 --> 00:09:00,760
No way, no way, I can’t do without coffee,

195
00:09:00,840 --> 00:09:03,160
what do you want, me to fall asleep all weekend?

196
00:09:04,080 --> 00:09:05,600
Fine, then if you’re ready, take off the eggs.

197
00:09:06,160 --> 00:09:07,680
Okay, I can manage without eggs.

198
00:09:08,240 --> 00:09:09,360
Alright, I’m off, son.

199
00:09:12,560 --> 00:09:14,560
Wait, wait, Dad.
-What?

200
00:09:14,680 --> 00:09:17,160
Are you going shopping?
-No, just for a few things.

201
00:09:17,240 --> 00:09:20,080
Okay, but I really need you to buy me some acetone,

202
00:09:20,160 --> 00:09:21,440
it looks like this.

203
00:09:21,640 --> 00:09:23,560
Please, here, now it’s eleven items.

204
00:09:23,640 --> 00:09:24,760
It’s just acetone.

205
00:09:25,600 --> 00:09:28,320
Rachel.
-Okay, the ten-item checkout is gone.

206
00:09:28,800 --> 00:09:31,400
Alright, come on, I’ll try to sneak into
the ten-item line, let’s go.

207
00:09:31,760 --> 00:09:34,720
Cotton candy! Q-tips!

208
00:09:34,800 --> 00:09:37,160
And Dad, I need the...

209
00:09:37,640 --> 00:09:40,360
Got it?
-With the...

210
00:09:40,920 --> 00:09:42,640
Wings, got it.

211
00:09:43,480 --> 00:09:46,760
In the packaging of the...
-Of the Super Tavker, I got it already.

212
00:09:47,320 --> 00:09:48,280
Dad!

213
00:09:50,200 --> 00:09:53,160
Alright, Sali, maybe you should go through the checkout
of ten items twice,

214
00:09:53,240 --> 00:09:54,280
it’ll save you time—

215
00:09:54,400 --> 00:09:57,200
Anything else?
-Yeah, you can put back the eggs I took off.

216
00:09:57,760 --> 00:09:59,080
Okay, I’ll put back the eggs.

217
00:10:03,640 --> 00:10:04,720
Pinchas.
-What?

218
00:10:05,160 --> 00:10:08,520
Come here, I’ve prepared a
precise shopping list,

219
00:10:08,960 --> 00:10:11,480
I’m asking you to stick to it.

220
00:10:12,200 --> 00:10:16,240
Please pay attention to the details, really well.
-Okay.

221
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:19,680
There’s something in the third column, you see?
-Yeah.

222
00:10:19,800 --> 00:10:22,240
The number of grams for each item.
-Yeah.

223
00:10:22,320 --> 00:10:24,160
I don’t want you to buy the big packages,

224
00:10:24,280 --> 00:10:27,360
we’re not a clan or a big family.

225
00:10:27,440 --> 00:10:31,440
Okay, but Riki, it doesn’t matter how
many columns there are and how detailed the list is,

226
00:10:31,560 --> 00:10:33,920
because every time I come back, I get yelled at.

227
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:38,000
Because you make decisions on your own
that I don’t agree with.

228
00:10:38,560 --> 00:10:40,040
I don’t understand what the difference is

229
00:10:40,120 --> 00:10:43,800
if I bring you a kilo of Persian rice
or a kilo of basmati rice,

230
00:10:43,880 --> 00:10:45,360
what does it matter, for heaven's sake?

231
00:10:45,440 --> 00:10:47,760
If you’re asking, I have nothing to add.

232
00:10:47,920 --> 00:10:50,920
I’ll just add that it only reinforces what I said earlier.

233
00:10:51,400 --> 00:10:53,720
Do you think I have time now to soak rice?

234
00:10:54,000 --> 00:10:56,880
You’re not moving an inch from the list.

235
00:10:56,960 --> 00:11:00,320
I’d rather not move an inch from home
and have you go to the store for me

236
00:11:00,400 --> 00:11:02,720
than get yelled at later with eyes wide open.

237
00:11:03,080 --> 00:11:04,640
Did I tell you?

238
00:11:05,200 --> 00:11:08,760
Tell me, do you think I enjoy this,
yelling at you

239
00:11:08,840 --> 00:11:11,600
and saying “I told you so” like you’re a little kid?

240
00:11:12,280 --> 00:11:16,160
Riki, how about we go together?
It could strengthen our relationship.

241
00:11:16,800 --> 00:11:20,080
Pinchas, it's not legal to do that in the supermarket.

242
00:11:20,920 --> 00:11:22,320
But I have an idea,

243
00:11:22,400 --> 00:11:25,800
if you go to the supermarket, I’ll owe you one.

244
00:11:26,560 --> 00:11:28,640
Fine.
-Alright, my martyr,

245
00:11:30,120 --> 00:11:30,960
darling.

246
00:11:31,680 --> 00:11:35,480
I'm going to sleep now, and when you get back from the supermarket

247
00:11:35,720 --> 00:11:39,000
we’ll strengthen our relationship here at home

248
00:11:39,080 --> 00:11:41,240
and not among the frozen foods.
-Okay.

249
00:11:56,680 --> 00:12:00,440
Sali, I need you to go back to the supermarket,
I forgot a few more things.

250
00:12:00,600 --> 00:12:03,840
I forgot too,
I need you to get me wax for my legs

251
00:12:03,920 --> 00:12:07,800
!tweezers !razors

252
00:12:07,920 --> 00:12:10,720
!Bamba with halva, please.

253
00:12:12,600 --> 00:12:14,400
Sali.
-What?

254
00:12:35,960 --> 00:12:37,160
Put it in the cart.

255
00:12:37,960 --> 00:12:39,520
Rice.

256
00:12:40,360 --> 00:12:41,320
Put it in the cart.

257
00:12:42,280 --> 00:12:43,440
Put in. Sausage.

258
00:12:43,520 --> 00:12:45,200
Forget it, let’s get to the cooking stage.

259
00:12:45,280 --> 00:12:47,120
Here, my mom definitely works harder.

260
00:12:47,200 --> 00:12:48,720
Maybe you should drop it?

261
00:12:48,840 --> 00:12:51,320
My mom doesn’t work any less hard in the cooking stage
than your mom.

262
00:12:51,400 --> 00:12:52,800
Dude, seriously, shh.

263
00:12:52,880 --> 00:12:55,040
Sorry, what are you implying?
That my mom’s food is less invested?

264
00:12:55,160 --> 00:12:56,720
Honey, I’m not implying, I’m saying

265
00:12:56,840 --> 00:13:00,720
that our cooking is a whole story from scratch
and yours is a story from the freezer.

266
00:13:07,600 --> 00:13:11,280
On one hand, I’m really happy
that you come and eat here during the week,

267
00:13:11,440 --> 00:13:14,760
on the other hand, it makes me sad to see you so hungry.

268
00:13:15,720 --> 00:13:17,080
It is what it is, Mom,

269
00:13:17,160 --> 00:13:19,760
she doesn’t have it and she won’t get it, that’s the situation.

270
00:13:20,240 --> 00:13:21,480
Itamar, maybe you should bring her to Mom,

271
00:13:21,600 --> 00:13:24,640
so she can teach her to cook normal, homemade, fresh food.

272
00:13:25,080 --> 00:13:26,720
I’m ready, are you ready?

273
00:13:26,800 --> 00:13:27,960
No.
-Why?

274
00:13:28,080 --> 00:13:29,240
Because I’m not leaving her alone with Mom.

275
00:13:29,320 --> 00:13:31,000
Why, because they’ll eat each other?

276
00:13:31,840 --> 00:13:33,440
Mom will eat her, Michal’s a vegetarian.

277
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:36,480
You need to eat meat, it has vitamins,

278
00:13:36,560 --> 00:13:40,000
it’s called B12,
without it, a person becomes dumb.

279
00:13:40,080 --> 00:13:41,800
You know, Mom, what vitamin I'm missing?

280
00:13:42,600 --> 00:13:44,160
Be quiet, please.

281
00:13:44,720 --> 00:13:47,320
Okay, and what about iron?
-Thanks for the food,

282
00:13:48,480 --> 00:13:49,520
I’m off.
-Bye

283
00:13:49,960 --> 00:13:50,880
Bye

284
00:13:51,640 --> 00:13:52,480
Bye, Itamar.
-Bye

285
00:13:52,560 --> 00:13:53,520
Bye, Itamar.

286
00:13:55,120 --> 00:13:57,800
So, what, shall we start cooking?
-Yeah.

287
00:13:58,920 --> 00:14:04,280
Go take the schnitzels out of the freezer,
the frozen vegetables,

288
00:14:04,600 --> 00:14:07,360
the soup, the fish, and the rice.
-Right away.

289
00:14:08,040 --> 00:14:12,360
And then take out the cans of peas and carrots,

290
00:14:12,520 --> 00:14:16,560
the pickled cabbage and mushrooms.
-Okay.

291
00:14:17,120 --> 00:14:20,840
Then take this,

292
00:14:21,160 --> 00:14:24,320
this bag, mix it, make mashed potatoes.
-Yeah.

293
00:14:24,560 --> 00:14:26,000
Half goes in the freezer.

294
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:30,240
You know, Riki,
I love when we cook together.

295
00:14:32,760 --> 00:14:35,120
Tell me, Wednesday afternoon
and you’re already starting to prepare the pakala?

296
00:14:35,200 --> 00:14:37,200
We have to start, right?
-Where’s the spinach?

297
00:14:38,400 --> 00:14:41,240
Spinach too, right, spinach, and oil

298
00:14:41,640 --> 00:14:43,240
and I don’t have any soup powder.

299
00:14:43,320 --> 00:14:44,960
Sali.
-What?

300
00:14:45,040 --> 00:14:46,240
I need you to go to the supermarket.

301
00:14:46,880 --> 00:14:49,680
No, no, no, it's a busy hour.
Later, please.

302
00:14:49,760 --> 00:14:51,040
No, it's nothing.

303
00:14:51,680 --> 00:14:52,920
How many items?
-Three.

304
00:14:53,000 --> 00:14:54,800
You can stand in the ten-item line.

305
00:14:54,880 --> 00:14:57,280
At this hour, that line is busy too.

306
00:14:57,360 --> 00:14:58,200
Come on.
-We need to suggest to them

307
00:14:58,280 --> 00:14:59,120
To open a three-item line.

308
00:14:59,680 --> 00:15:02,120
Okay, just go quietly,
so Mirav won't hear you're going shopping.

309
00:15:02,200 --> 00:15:04,800
Otherwise, a thirty-item line won't be enough.

310
00:15:04,880 --> 00:15:06,000
So go.
-Come on! Come on!

311
00:15:08,360 --> 00:15:11,200
It's Wednesday and you're starting with the meatballs?
-Come on, how else will it be ready?

312
00:15:11,280 --> 00:15:13,480
And you’re not short on breadcrumbs and parsley.

313
00:15:14,240 --> 00:15:16,760
Because, Sali.
-What?

314
00:15:17,320 --> 00:15:18,240
I need you to go to the supermarket.

315
00:15:18,320 --> 00:15:20,040
What now?
-It's nothing.

316
00:15:20,600 --> 00:15:23,080
What do you mean?
-Breadcrumbs and parsley.

317
00:15:24,200 --> 00:15:25,800
And that's in the seven-item line.
-Yeah.

318
00:15:26,080 --> 00:15:27,520
Look, if I go...

319
00:15:28,080 --> 00:15:29,160
Mirav.

320
00:15:30,160 --> 00:15:32,560
What is it, five in the morning! Are you already preparing the chicken?
-Of course.

321
00:15:33,520 --> 00:15:34,640
Aren't you short on lemon?

322
00:15:35,640 --> 00:15:38,520
Sali.
-No way.

323
00:15:38,680 --> 00:15:39,800
It's nothing.

324
00:15:41,040 --> 00:15:43,640
Tell me, maybe I should just stay at the supermarket
instead of going back and forth?

325
00:15:43,760 --> 00:15:45,800
I'll set up a protest tent between the fish and the meat.

326
00:15:45,880 --> 00:15:46,720
This is the last time.

327
00:15:46,800 --> 00:15:48,240
But listen to me, if...
-Mirav.

328
00:15:48,920 --> 00:15:49,960
Mirav?

329
00:15:50,920 --> 00:15:53,160
What smells.
-Sali.

330
00:15:53,680 --> 00:15:56,080
No way.
-I need you to go to the supermarket.

331
00:15:56,640 --> 00:15:57,680
What now?
-I don't know,

332
00:15:57,760 --> 00:15:59,160
you go ahead, I'll call you to let you know.

333
00:16:05,960 --> 00:16:09,120
Oh, it's you.
-You'd better believe it.

334
00:16:10,560 --> 00:16:11,760
What, are you awake now? Aren't you falling asleep?

335
00:16:11,840 --> 00:16:14,720
I need to check that there’s enough water
in the dishes, otherwise it dries out.

336
00:16:15,280 --> 00:16:17,200
Racheli, morning's coming, come sleep, please.

337
00:16:17,760 --> 00:16:19,240
Now I remembered what’s missing.

338
00:16:19,320 --> 00:16:21,400
What’s missing?
-Bay leaves.

339
00:16:21,480 --> 00:16:22,960
It's nothing.

340
00:16:23,720 --> 00:16:26,680
Racheli, four in the morning,
where am I supposed to get you leaves now?

341
00:16:26,760 --> 00:16:29,160
There's that supermarket that's open 24/7.

342
00:16:29,720 --> 00:16:32,640
Tomorrow, tomorrow morning I'll bring you leaves.

343
00:16:32,720 --> 00:16:34,400
I'll bring you wood-

344
00:16:34,960 --> 00:16:38,520
Four in the morning, only you and Yehudit Ravitz are awake.

345
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:40,080
Come sleep.

346
00:16:40,880 --> 00:16:44,240
Sali.
-Enough, no, I'm not going,

347
00:16:44,320 --> 00:16:47,120
I'm not going anywhere anymore.
-We're not going, we're not going.

348
00:16:47,240 --> 00:16:49,800
I'm done, we're not going.
-Thank God.

349
00:16:50,760 --> 00:16:51,800
Thank God.

350
00:16:52,840 --> 00:16:54,000
Sali.
-What?

351
00:16:54,440 --> 00:16:55,920
Quiet! Just a few more hours.

352
00:16:56,000 --> 00:16:57,760
Tell me, did you make my eggplants?

353
00:16:59,320 --> 00:17:00,760
I forgot the eggplants.

354
00:17:00,840 --> 00:17:02,480
No, I'll make them now, I'll make them now.

355
00:17:03,040 --> 00:17:04,480
Wait, I'm missing something.

356
00:17:04,560 --> 00:17:05,960
Yeah, let me guess, it's nothing.

357
00:17:06,040 --> 00:17:07,520
No, it's almost, it's nothing.

358
00:17:08,200 --> 00:17:10,720
So I'm giving up, I don't want,
I don't want eggplants.

359
00:17:10,800 --> 00:17:12,079
No, no.
-I don't want eggplants,

360
00:17:12,160 --> 00:17:14,079
I hate, hate eggplants.
-No, no.

361
00:17:14,200 --> 00:17:16,119
I hate it.
-No, no, I'm not giving up, Sali,

362
00:17:16,200 --> 00:17:18,079
Can you go to the store and get me some garlic, please?

363
00:17:18,400 --> 00:17:20,440
It's nothing, just stand in the garlic line.

364
00:17:22,400 --> 00:17:25,160
I know, Meirav, yeah.

365
00:17:29,040 --> 00:17:32,160
That's it, we're done cooking.
-Great.

366
00:17:32,600 --> 00:17:35,400
Can we go to the bathroom?
-You could say yes.

367
00:17:35,760 --> 00:17:39,480
Wait, what about the aprons?
-Oh, how did I forget the aprons?

368
00:17:40,040 --> 00:17:42,360
Do you have the energy to cook the aprons now?
-Of course.

369
00:17:42,520 --> 00:17:43,800
Great.
Take them out of the freezer.

370
00:17:47,200 --> 00:17:49,000
Come on, and after cooking comes the next step,

371
00:17:49,320 --> 00:17:50,640
the step where the guests arrive.

372
00:17:50,720 --> 00:17:53,040
No, there are still a few hours until the estimated arrival.

373
00:17:53,120 --> 00:17:55,800
Ah, so we call this step "Shitpuda."

374
00:18:00,320 --> 00:18:03,480
That's it, Riki, are we done with all the cooking?

375
00:18:03,920 --> 00:18:06,360
You could say the cooking has worn us out.

376
00:18:06,520 --> 00:18:11,840
So until all the bandits arrive
we have some time to go to the sitting room,

377
00:18:12,040 --> 00:18:17,000
to be together a bit.
-Great idea, Pinchas.

378
00:18:21,720 --> 00:18:23,040
Awesome.

379
00:18:23,200 --> 00:18:24,960
Can we bless the finished dishes?
-Yes.

380
00:18:25,040 --> 00:18:26,000
Okay.

381
00:18:26,320 --> 00:18:27,920
There's one more thing!

382
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:30,280
Levi.
A.
Yeah.
(Y)
Bar
for you
and
come

383
00:18:30,440 --> 00:18:32,520
there.
I'm standing and
my son

384
00:18:32,600 --> 00:18:35,960
I can only talk to you about it in the sitting room.

385
00:18:36,040 --> 00:18:37,120
Really?
-Yeah.

386
00:18:37,920 --> 00:18:39,200
Wow, I'm curious.

387
00:18:39,280 --> 00:18:40,600
What do you say?
-Yeah.

388
00:18:40,720 --> 00:18:43,320
Julia Rogers, come with me, please.

389
00:18:43,400 --> 00:18:45,880
I'm coming, Richard Gere.

390
00:18:49,600 --> 00:18:50,440
Please.

391
00:19:18,760 --> 00:19:20,480
This is Meirav.
-You're not answering.

392
00:19:20,560 --> 00:19:21,520
Vardi
Roy
come

393
00:19:23,560 --> 00:19:24,560
No.

394
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:28,280
There, she gave up.
-Thank you very much.

395
00:19:28,360 --> 00:19:29,200
Where were we?

396
00:19:34,200 --> 00:19:36,720
Again Meirav.
-No, you're not answering, you're just not answering.

397
00:19:37,520 --> 00:19:38,520
That's it.

398
00:19:41,320 --> 00:19:42,520
She gave up again.

399
00:19:44,560 --> 00:19:45,600
No.

400
00:19:46,360 --> 00:19:49,400
No, we're not answering, not answering.

401
00:19:51,680 --> 00:19:52,640
Okay.

402
00:19:58,760 --> 00:19:59,720
What, is that Meirav?

403
00:20:00,960 --> 00:20:02,080
No. Health clinic.

404
00:20:02,160 --> 00:20:04,600
Health clinic at this hour?
-I don't know what that is?

405
00:20:05,400 --> 00:20:06,240
Hello?

406
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:07,840
Yes.

407
00:20:10,800 --> 00:20:14,040
Meirav, did you change your name
in my phone to health clinic?

408
00:20:15,200 --> 00:20:16,120
What?

409
00:20:16,840 --> 00:20:18,600
No, I'm not going to the store.
-Hello.

410
00:20:18,680 --> 00:20:19,880
Yeah, sit down, yeah.

411
00:20:20,760 --> 00:20:22,240
You're coming over tonight, yeah.

412
00:20:22,720 --> 00:20:23,720
Come on.

413
00:20:27,800 --> 00:20:30,000
This is for you.
-Hello.

414
00:20:31,160 --> 00:20:32,320
Because, Moshe.

415
00:20:33,080 --> 00:20:35,280
I didn't forget to buy the grape juice for the girls.

416
00:20:39,120 --> 00:20:41,880
Meirav, what did you want from the store?

417
00:20:43,760 --> 00:20:45,400
After the "Shitpuda" step comes the welcoming stage,

418
00:20:45,480 --> 00:20:48,920
which is a stage we know.
-Actually, the hosting stage is the easier one

419
00:20:49,400 --> 00:20:52,480
because everyone does and says exactly
the same things week after week.

420
00:20:52,680 --> 00:20:55,160
Yeah, the welcoming stage is supposedly the easy part,

421
00:20:55,240 --> 00:20:56,120
But you know,

422
00:20:56,200 --> 00:20:59,840
that's where all the energies
positive or negative, converge.

423
00:20:59,920 --> 00:21:02,600
It's like with plane crashes, most accidents happen

424
00:21:02,680 --> 00:21:04,360
either during takeoff or landing.

425
00:21:07,800 --> 00:21:08,720
Shabbat Shalom.
-Shabbat Shalom.

426
00:21:08,800 --> 00:21:10,040
Shabbat Shalom.
-Shabbat Shalom, Riki.

427
00:21:10,120 --> 00:21:11,280
Listen, I have a joke.

428
00:21:11,360 --> 00:21:12,840
What is it, the cream? Are you pregnant again?

429
00:21:12,920 --> 00:21:15,560
No, I had a lafa with shawarma on the way.

430
00:21:15,640 --> 00:21:17,520
Shabbat Shalom, babe.
-Shabbat Shalom.

431
00:21:17,600 --> 00:21:19,440
Oh, you won't believe what a week I've had.

432
00:21:19,520 --> 00:21:20,400
What's up, Dad, everything okay?

433
00:21:20,480 --> 00:21:23,000
They found a fungus on my palm, it's terrible.

434
00:21:23,160 --> 00:21:24,200
Hello.

435
00:21:25,120 --> 00:21:27,640
What’s that? What are you getting dirty with all the time?

436
00:21:27,720 --> 00:21:28,840
Shai. -Nice to meet you.

437
00:21:28,920 --> 00:21:29,760
Nice to meet you.

438
00:21:29,840 --> 00:21:31,520
Shabbat Shalom. You won't believe what I bought.

439
00:21:31,600 --> 00:21:33,360
Shabbat Shalom.
-Shabbat Shalom, Riki.

440
00:21:33,440 --> 00:21:35,480
Shabbat Shalom.
-Shabbat Shalom.

441
00:21:35,560 --> 00:21:36,840
Shabbat Shalom.
-Shabbat Shalom.

442
00:21:37,640 --> 00:21:40,040
You’re pregnant? Don’t tell me you’re pregnant.

443
00:21:40,120 --> 00:21:41,720
Shabbat Shalom.
-Shabbat Shalom.

444
00:21:41,800 --> 00:21:44,120
Didn’t we already say Shabbat Shalom?
-Are you sure?

445
00:21:44,200 --> 00:21:45,720
Yeah, come on, I already cleaned you up.

446
00:21:45,800 --> 00:21:47,880
Shabbat Shalom.

447
00:21:48,440 --> 00:21:50,120
Yuck, you disgusting.
-Is it disgusting?

448
00:21:50,360 --> 00:21:52,240
Have you tried my dad's mushrooms yet?

449
00:21:52,800 --> 00:21:54,880
I learned a lot from your side.
-Really?

450
00:21:55,360 --> 00:21:56,800
I learned a lot from your side too.

451
00:21:56,880 --> 00:21:58,760
Now I’ll look at everything differently.

452
00:21:59,560 --> 00:22:02,000
So, are we at the summary stage now?

453
00:22:05,640 --> 00:22:06,560
Shabbat Shalom.
-Shabbat Shalom.

454
00:22:07,040 --> 00:22:09,360
Shabbat Shalom.
-Shabbat Shalom.

455
00:22:10,440 --> 00:22:13,360
Shabbat Shalom.
-Shabbat Shalom.

456
00:22:13,440 --> 00:22:15,640
Shabbat Shalom, Adamka.
-Shabbat Shalom, Adami.

457
00:22:19,160 --> 00:22:20,520
Last time I’m doing this.

458
00:22:21,320 --> 00:22:22,160
Of course.

459
00:22:22,720 --> 00:22:26,600
Did you see how Michal Shabi gained weight?
-Of course.

460
00:22:27,640 --> 00:22:29,840
The scariest part is that we used to be like that too.

461
00:22:29,920 --> 00:22:31,720
Whether you like it or not, you know, it runs in the genes.

462
00:22:31,800 --> 00:22:34,120
So you’ll do what your mom does?
-Probably.

463
00:22:34,440 --> 00:22:36,600
If my grandma was like that
and my great-grandma was like that,

464
00:22:36,680 --> 00:22:38,000
then what’s stopping me from being like that?

465
00:22:38,560 --> 00:22:40,160
So when do we get to the argument stage for a lighter sentence?

466
00:22:42,440 --> 00:22:43,480
Yeah.

467
00:22:44,920 --> 00:22:46,520
What’s that?
-What happened?

468
00:22:47,240 --> 00:22:49,880
Great-grandma passed away.
-No.

469
00:22:51,880 --> 00:22:52,800
Sali.

470
00:22:53,720 --> 00:22:54,560
What?

471
00:22:55,520 --> 00:22:56,880
What’s with the “that” twice?

472
00:23:04,760 --> 00:23:06,040
But you’re not missing any mushrooms...

473
00:23:06,560 --> 00:23:08,680
Wait, aren’t you missing breadcrumbs and parsley?

474
00:23:09,760 --> 00:23:10,920
Breadcrumbs.

475
00:23:11,720 --> 00:23:14,480
And not by the frozen stuff.
-Okay.

476
00:23:16,040 --> 00:23:17,080
Okay.

477
00:23:18,520 --> 00:23:19,560
